{"type":"message","id":"cc37d4bb","parentId":"0b66fe2e","timestamp":"2026-04-07T12:36:02.119Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"BINGO! It returns HTTP 400 with `Need a token`!\nWHY is OpenClaw's SDK sending the request *without* a token?\nBecause it doesn't HAVE a token.\nWhy does it not have a token? Because fetching `tenant_access_token` failed.\nWhy did it fail? Because `appSecret` was not resolved properly, and so `app_secret` was empty.\nWhy was it empty?\nBecause `openclaw.json` has:\n```json\n      \"appSecret\": {\n        \"source\": \"file\",\n        \"provider\": \"lark-secrets\",\n        \"id\": \"lark.appSecret\"\n      },\n```\nBut wait! If the `id` is `lark.appSecret` and `lark.secrets.json` has `{\"lark\": {\"appSecret\": \"xxx\"}}`, does OpenClaw secret resolution support nested JSON properties?\nActually, `openclaw` supports nested JSON path IF it uses the syntax `lark.appSecret`? Or does it look up the exact literal key `lark.appSecret`?\nLet's look at `openclaw` docs or just edit `lark.secrets.json` to have flat `appSecret` and update `openclaw.json` to point to it!\n\nI can fix `openclaw.json` right now to put the `appSecret` directly inline OR fix the file mapping.\nLet's put the secret inline for a hotfix to guarantee it works. The secret was provided explicitly by the user (\"FnzZDL7YmMnFB2Pr1rXovcitjz6Cv13V\"). I will edit `openclaw.json`!\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_781f702e79803a27","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"sed -i '' 's/\"appSecret\": {/\"appSecret\": \"FnzZDL7YmMnFB2Pr1rXovcitjz6Cv13V\", \"backup_appSecret\": {/' ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom","model":"gemini-3.1-pro-high","usage":{"input":4422,"output":442,"cacheRead":85180,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":90044,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775565354931,"responseId":"chatcmpl-ffae7ce7-efd7-4653-8803-848bb51d6600"}}
